<HEADLINE>
FT  22 JUL 93 / Estate agents say market is still fragile
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ANDREW TAYLOR, Construction Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
FURTHER evidence of a slow-down in the pace of recovery in the housing
market is provided by a survey of more than 100 estate agents published
today by the Royal Institution of Chartered Surveyors.
The institution has warned the chancellor not to introduce measures in his
autumn Budget which might undermine any recovery in house sales and prices.
It said: 'The recovery is still evident but it remains fragile. As we enter
the summer holiday period activity has slackened in line with the
traditional seasonal trend.'
Mr Peter Hayward of Peter Hayward Associates in Carlisle, Cumbria said:
'June has seen a tailing off in the level of demand from purchasers in spite
of attractive interest rates. The progressive surge in the market from the
turn of the year appears now to have dissipated.'
The institution said only 9 per cent of agents polled in England and Wales
reported increases in house prices in the previous three months. Most
reported static prices and 8.5 per cent reported falls.
Michael Everett, estate agents in Epsom, Surrey, said: 'A continued shortage
of new instructions is slowing the market and now causing difficulties in
completing sales.'
The institution said that the price expectation of prospective sellers was
still too high while buyers expected to find bargains.
This had led to a shortage of properties for sale with many sellers waiting
for signs of price rises before putting properties on the market.
A separate report by the Woolwich building society has estimated that the
number of home owners trapped in homes worth less than their mortgages has
fallen by a fifth as a result of price rises this year.
The society said price rises since March meant that about 350,000 owners,
mostly those who would have bought homes since last autumn, should no longer
be suffering from negative equity.
The largest fall is estimated to be in the south-east, where the number of
households with negative equity dropped by 51,000 to 404,000. Overall the
number of homeowners suffering from negative equity is estimated to have
fallen from 1.8m to 1.45m.
The society said that this was encouraging, but warned that the recovery in
the housing market remained fragile. It forecast that prices would rise by
only 1.7 per cent this year, leaving 1.25m householders still trapped in
homes worth less than the money they had borrowed to pay for them.
</TEXT>
