<HEADLINE>
FT  22 JUL 93 / Building orders increase by 6%
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ANDREW TAYLOR
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
CONSTRUCTION orders jumped by 6 per cent during the three months to the end
of May compared with the corresponding months last year, according to
figures published yesterday by the Department of the Environment.
Orders also rose by 2 per cent compared with the previous three months.
Building industry leaders, however, said the figures belied the extent of
the downturn rather than pointing to a recovery in the industry, which was
still depressed in many parts.
Miss Joanne Cutler, economist at the Building Employers Confederation, said
that March had been a particularly good month for orders in the public
sector as authorities had rushed to spend their budgets before the end of
the financial year.
This had distorted comparisons with previous quarters. Indeed the
depart-ment's figures showed that orders had fallen in the two following
months, said Miss Cutler.
Contractors were particularly concerned that the government might reduce
public investment on construction as part of its effort to reduce a Pounds
50bn public sector borrowing requirement. This would compound recent
increases in the price of building materials which were squeezing
contractors' profit margins.
Government figures also revealed a 13 per cent increase in orders for
private housing and a 2 per cent increase in private industrial orders
compared with the corresponding months last year.
</TEXT>
