<HEADLINE>
FT  22 JUL 93 / Pounds 800m in savings tax rebates unclaimed
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By RICHARD LAPPER
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
MORE THAN 6m people have failed to claim back Pounds 800m owed to them by
the Inland Revenue, the Commons public accounts committee reported
yesterday.
The money relates to tax paid on savings accounts since the abolition of
composite rate tax in April 1991.
Most of the potential claimants are pensioners, children and married women
not at work whose income is less than the annual allowance of Pounds 3,445
and so do not have to pay tax on interest earnings. They are eligible to
receive interest income gross of tax.
Thousands of other claimants with earnings below Pounds 6,000, who pay
income tax only at the lower 20 per cent band, are also failing to claim
back tax that has been charged on their accounts at a rate of 25 per cent.
In its report published yesterday the committee says it notes the Revenue's
efforts to encourage people to claim, and adds that it considers the Revenue
'should now establish the reason for the substantial shortfall in claims'.
The claimants are owed an average of about Pounds 130 each, the committee's
report says.
In spite of official encouragement for people to claim, including extensive
television and newspaper advertising, fewer than 1 1/2 m eligible people
have applied for refunds.
The report says the Revenue believed 'misunderstanding and a reluctance to
get involved in form filling' were responsible for lack of claims.
To complicate matters, a further 1m people have registered incorrectly,
again due to 'misunderstanding'.
Only five of the 24 Inland Revenue offices set up to deal with the expected
claims for repayment are used for this purpose. Of the remainder, four have
been closed and 15 diverted to other uses. The committee says it was worried
by the 'waste of expenditure'.
The report was also critical of apparent reluctance by the Revenue to
investigate the tax affairs of farmers, who are suspected of widespread
evasion.
The Revenue told the committee that farming 'had its own special mysteries,
and that there was a risk these could discourage the ordinary tax
inspector'.
The committee says: 'We do not regard this as an acceptable reason for not
pursuing tax in what appears clearly to be a high-risk area.' The Revenue is
also criticised in the report for duplicating repayments of corporation tax
and petroleum revenue tax totalling Pounds 50.4m.
The duplications were a result of 'serious systems' failures'.
Inland Revenue: Account Matters. HMSO. Pounds 8.95
</TEXT>
<XX>
Countries:-
</XX>
<CN>GBZ  United Kingdom, EC.
</CN>
