<HEADLINE>
FT  22 JUL 93 / Sedgefield battles with surprise rivals: With the new map of
assisted areas due tomorrow Chris Tighe reviews the fight for funds
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By CHRIS TIGHE
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
WHEN THE government reveals the redrawn map of assisted areas Mr John
Litherland, planning director for Sedgefield district council, will be
listening on his personal stereo at the office. It will be a tense moment.
For years the County Durham district has battled to replace jobs lost by the
rundown of traditional industries in its area. But this time round its
economic development team has been astonished to discover the identity of
its rivals.
For the announcement, expected tomorrow, will be of equal interest in the
south-east.
At a conference on economic development held as the recession hit southern
areas, Mr Litherland found himself in the company of delegates from the home
counties - even, he recalls, from Hertfordshire - searching for ways to
tackle the unfamiliar problem of unemployment.
'There was a degree of suspicion at their presence from people from the
longstanding assisted areas,' he admits. Caution, it seems, was merited.
'They were learning very quickly.' Just how quickly can be judged from the
intense competition unleashed last June when the government announced its
assisted areas review.
The map designates development areas and lower-ranked intermediate areas
where companies which set up or expand can qualify for regional selective
assistance and regional enterprise grants.
About 2,000 submissions pleading to retain, or gain, designation swamped the
Department of Trade and Industry.
Sedgefield district has more at stake than most. Its south-west is in the
Bishop Auckland travel-to-work-area, currently a development area. The rest
of the district is in Durham travel-to-work-area, an intermediate area.
According to DTI figures assistance grants worth Pounds 45.4m were approved
between 1984 and 1992 for companies in the Bishop Auckland area. In the
Durham area the figure was Pounds 12.5m.
Mr Litherland realised there could be no complacency about the review. The
Bishop Auckland area's jobless rate of 11.7 per cent, just 1.4 percentage
points above the British average, means its development area status could be
at risk.
The Durham status looks vulnerable too, due to below national average
unemployment. But by scouring the league table of the 322
travel-to-work-areas, Mr Litherland's team found a possible trump card.
Durham ranks seventh in youth unemployment.
Development area rating, Mr Litherland argues, is imperative to attract
job-creating inward investors. Sedgefield has netted many inward investors
including the Japanese electronics group Fujitsu, whose microchip
manufacturing site at Newton Aycliffe, an eventual investment of Pounds
600m, has been promised Pounds 30m in regional selective assistance.
Yet, in spite of many years of regional grants Sedgefield's job creation is
not even standing still.
The growth of small businesses has been unable to compensate for heavy job
losses by bigger companies. Total employment in the district fell from
35,000 in 1981 to 31,340 at the end of 1989.
Mr Litherland's southern rivals argue that they too face the challenge of
economic restructuring. But Mr Litherland said: 'The move out of recession
is likely to evaporate their problems. In our case it's going to be a
continuing battle to attempt to achieve self sustaining growth.'
</TEXT>
<XX>
Countries:-
</XX>
<CN>GBZ  United Kingdom, EC.
</CN>
<XX>
Industries:-
</XX>
<IN>P9121 Legislative Bodies.
</IN>
