<HEADLINE>
FT  22 JUL 93 / Mercury's regulation plea
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ANDREW ADONIS
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
MERCURY, the main competitor to British Telecommunications, yesterday called
for more 'focused' regulation of the telecoms industry. It also warned
against over-regulation.
Its call came in its response to draft proposals by Oftel, the industry
regulator, which would force BT to account separately for its 'retail' and
'network' businesses in an attempt to promote greater competition.
Rather than full accounting separation on Oftel's model, Mercury wants Oftel
to concentrate on prices that BT charges competitors for 'bottleneck'
services - those over which it has a virtual monopoly. The most significant
is access to BT's local network to 'deliver' calls the last leg of their
journey.
Mr Terry Rhodes, Mercury director of competition policy, said: 'We want to
see more focused regulation, not an increase in regulation all round.'
Mr Rhodes welcomed BT's proposal for a 'menu' of prices for particular
services as 'a big step in the right direction' - but said that the basis
for apportioning costs for each service needed to be refined.
Mercury's submission marks a significant development in its attitude to
regulation, reflecting its status as an increasingly effective competitor to
BT. The cable TV companies, still fighting to establish themselves, want to
see a bigger Oftel able to monitor and check BT's activities in detail.
</TEXT>
