<HEADLINE>
FT  22 JUL 93 / Goldman faces Maxwell action
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By NORMA COHEN, Investments Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
TRUSTEES of two pension schemes formerly controlled by Robert Maxwell are
considering filing legal claims against Goldman Sachs, the US investment
bank, for up to Pounds 56m in connection with transactions it handled on
behalf of the schemes, the Commons social security committee was told
yesterday.
The funds are the proceeds of 25,000 shares in Maxwell Communication
Corporation purchased from the Mirror Group Newspapers scheme and the
Maxwell Communication Corporation works scheme by Goldman Sachs on the
instructions of Mr Kevin Maxwell on May 29 1991. The shares were later
re-purchased from Goldman by two Liechtenstein-based trusts controlled by
Maxwell family interests.
Goldman Sachs has said it was acting on Mr Kevin Maxwell's instructions when
it paid the proceeds not to the pension schemes but to Bishopsgate
Investment Trust, which Mr Kevin Maxwell described as a nominee company for
the pension-fund manager.
Separately, Mr Brian Tatch, chairman of the board of trustees to the MCC
works scheme, told the committee that he had met early yesterday with the
Securities and Investments Board, the City's chief regulatory watchdog,
regarding possible help in compelling Goldman Sachs to return the assets.
Mr Tatch said SIB informed the trustees that it is unlikely to have any
jurisdiction since the transaction appeared to have been booked in New York.
Mr Shaw has asked if the Securities and Exchange Commission, the US
watchdog, is investigating the transactions.
The pension funds have argued that Mr Kevin Maxwell did not have legal
authority to order specific transactions on behalf of the schemes, and that
Goldman Sachs should have taken more care to determine whether his
instructions were proper.
Goldman Sachs said yesterday: 'Detailed information about the trades has
been provided to all regulatory authorities which have asked about them. We
would expect to do the same if any additional inquiries are made. We believe
we acted properly in connection with these transactions.'
</TEXT>
