<HEADLINE>
FT  22 JUL 93 / BR maintenance arm to be sold
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By RICHARD TOMKINS, Transport Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
BRITISH RAIL'S train maintenance activities, which employ 2,400 people
around the country, are to be privatised next year, the government announced
yesterday.
The move could mean heavy job losses because the operations will have to
compete with the private sector in an industry burdened by overcapacity. The
activities to be sold are the maintenance depots at Eastleigh, Doncaster,
Wolverton and Glasgow and other facilities at Chart Leacon, Ilford, and
Swindon.
The depots are responsible for heavy maintenance and repair of BR rolling
stock. Lighter maintenance activities will stay with BR - but on
privatisation will pass to Railtrack, the proposed track-owning company of
the railway.
Mr Roger Freeman, minister for public transport, said train maintenance was
suffering from overcapacity because of advances in rolling stock technology
in the last 20 to 30 years.
But he said the privatisation of BR's maintenance depots could bring
benefits because they would have greater freedom to diversify and compete
for work outside the railway supply industry.
The depots to be sold had a combined turnover of Pounds 228.3m in the
financial year 1992-93, but made only marginal profits.
Mr Freeman said he expected the depots to be sold either to private sector
companies or to internal buy-out teams, but he added: 'No one is going to
pretend in current economic circumstances that the sale will yield
significant sums of money.'
</TEXT>
