<HEADLINE>
FT  22 JUL 93 / Struggle to find mining investors: Operating profits are up
but, coal's future looks even more uncertain
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By MICHAEL SMITH
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
IT WAS hardly the perfect prelude to privatisation. Yesterday's results from
British Coal were not the worst in the corporation's 45 years in the public
sector - but they are potentially more harmful.
The reported losses for 1992-93 of Pounds 588m compare to the biggest loss
of Pounds 5bn in 1990 after the corporation initiated a capital
restructuring. But coming just months before the government is due to
present its coal privatisation bill to parliament they increase the
difficulties ministers have in persuading financiers and industrialists that
British Coal has a healthy future in the private sector.
The government will argue, as British Coal executives did yesterday, that
last year's losses were exceptional, brought about by an unusual combination
of heavy asset write-offs and pit closure costs.
The figure they will stress is the operating profit of Pounds 545m, some
Pounds 123m higher than the previous year and bettered only in 1986 when
there were unusual circumstances following the national pits strike. This is
indeed a success story and reflects a growing ability to bring costs under
control.
There has been an impressive increase in productivity to 7.49 tonnes per
manshift - after a doubling to 6.34 tonnes per manshift between 1985-86 and
the end of last year. Meanwhile overhead, or 'above pit', costs have been
halved in the past four years.
Both trends will continue in the current year as the corporation proceeds
with plans to reduce by half the number of white-collar staff and takes
advantage of government proposals to allow changes in working patterns among
miners by, for example, allowing them to work longer shifts.
Next year's operating profits will be affected by a fall in the price of
coal to electricity generators and a potential further decline in the
contribution from opencast operations which was, until last year, a
significant element in profits growth. In 1992-93, opencast contributed
Pounds 160m to operating profits, down from Pounds 171m in 1991-92.
The main factor affecting opencast was the increasing difficulty of winning
planning permission. Increased concern about the environment is likely to
reduce tonnages - down from 16.7m to 15m last year - still further.
Next year's exceptional losses are likely to be less onerous than in
1992-93. Mr Ray Proctor, British Coal finance director, said yesterday that
the Pounds 636m write-down of assets and stock, taken as an exceptional
loss, was intended to reflect the fall in prices in the current five-year
contracts with generators.
This means they are unlikely to be repeated when the corporation outlines
its annual report for this year, probably the last before privatisation.
Exceptional costs associated with pit closures will, however, recur in
1993-94. Last year's Pounds 235m is associated with 18 pits kept open for
more than six months after British Coal announced their closure.
Most of them are still being maintained, but not mined for more than three
months into this financial year. More pit closures are on the way among the
12 mines reprieved in March and possibly among the 19 core pits.
These closures will cost money to implement and will dent this year's
profitability and British Coal's image further. They may, however, help to
assure potential purchasers that the corporation is down to a size that the
market can sustain and that exceptional costs will end before the industry
is privatised.
The government's ability to sell British Coal will depend on a variety of
factors, including whether it splits the corporation up and whether it
underwrites potential subsidence. The crucial factor for any prospective
purchaser will be whether the coal can be sold.
The difficulty in predicting that was underlined yesterday when Mr Neil
Clarke, British Coal chairman, said the outlook had worsened considerably
since the white paper in March as nuclear power and gas had performed better
than expected.
British Coal now believes that on top of contracts it already has with
electricity generators there will be space in the market for 11m tonnes of
black fuels - coal or oil or orimulsion - which it could compete for.
</TEXT>
<XX>
Companies:-
</XX>
<CO>British Coal Corp.
</CO>
<XX>
Countries:-
</XX>
<CN>GBZ  United Kingdom, EC.
</CN>
<XX>
Industries:-
</XX>
<IN>P1222 Bituminous Coal-Underground.
</IN>
<XX>
