<HEADLINE>
FT  22 JUL 93 / Business parks' vacancies hit 20%
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By VANESSA HOULDER
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE AFTERMATH of recession and a surge in development activity in the late
1980s has left a fifth of office space in business parks empty, DTZ Debenham
Thorpe, property advisers, have found, Vanessa Houlder writes.
The vacancy rate, higher than any other sector in the property industry,
reflects the immaturity of the market. Business parks emerged in the late
1980s as a result of a relaxation of planning controls and tenants' desire
to escape from town centres. Development reached a peak in 1990 when 17m sq
ft of space in business parks was built.
Wales and the east Midlands has the greatest proportion of empty space in
business parks, with 40 per cent on offer. The lowest rate is in Yorkshire
and Humberside with 10 per cent vacant.
Demand fell last year because of recessionary pressures, including the fall
in town-centre rents, which removed business parks' cost advantages. The
take-up of space last year fell to 3m sq ft, a 75 per cent drop on the peak
levels in 1989.
The most important users of business parks are the public sector and
industrial companies, which accounted for 45 per cent of all space occupied
on business parks between 1990 and last year.
Business Parks, Prospects for the 1990s. DTZ Debenham Thorpe, 44 Brook
Street, London W1A 4AG. Free.
</TEXT>
