<HEADLINE>
FT  22 JUL 93 / Parliament and Politics: Government faces gloomy arithmetic
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ALISON SMITH
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE parliamentary arithmetic still looks against the government for
tonight's vote.
In theory the Conservatives should be able to rely on 332 MPs, giving them a
majority of 18 over all the opposition parties. Since Sir James Kilfedder,
the Ulster Popular Unionist MP has said that he will vote with the
government tonight, the paper majority rises to 20.
On this basis it would take only 11 Tory rebels to vote with the opposition
to defeat the government. Or the majority could be overturned if a smaller
number of rebels voted with the opposition and other Euro-sceptics
abstained.
Almost all the opposition parties have a clear interest in voting against
the government. Labour itself makes up 269 of the total. The 21 Liberal
Democrats are set to line up with Labour, along with the four Plaid Cymru
MPs, the four SDLP MPs, the three Scottish Nationalists and the three
Democratic Unionists.
The unknown factor is the Ulster unionists, with nine MPs, the fourth
largest party in the Commons.
While it is unlikely that they would vote with the government even if a deal
were reached, they might all abstain. If so, the government's paper majority
would rise to 29. This would mean that for ministers to be defeated 15
Tories would have to vote against their party. Again, if some sceptics
abstained, a government defeat would be achieved with fewer rebels voting
with the opposition.
State of the parties:
Conservative                              332
Labour                                    269
Liberal Democrats                          21
Ulster unionists                            9
Plaid Cymru                                 4
SDLP                                        4
SNP                                         3
Democratic unionists                        3
Popular unionist                            1
TOTAL                                     646
(Excludes the Speaker and her three deputies, and takes account of
vacant seat)
</TEXT>
