<HEADLINE>
FT  22 JUL 93 / Parliament and Politics: Labour leads Britain's local
authority associations
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JOHN AUTHERS
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
LABOUR leads all of Britain's local authority associations, following the
election of a Labour chairman by the Association of District Councils, John
Authers writes.
The ADC, which had been chaired by Conservatives continuously since it was
formed in 1974, elected Ms Margaret Singh, a Labour councillor from Reading,
Berkshire, at its biennial meeting yesterday.
But Labour does not have overall control of the ADC, and the previous Tory
chairman, Lady Elizabeth Anson, is now deputy chairman. Labour has 58 seats
on the ADC's council, with 55 for the Conservatives, 17 Liberal Democrats
and 11 Independents.
</TEXT>
