<HEADLINE>
FT  22 JUL 93 / Parliament and Politics: MP says report shows need for extra
teachers
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JOHN AUTHERS
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
AN EXTRA 6,710 teachers will be needed next year to stop class sizes in
England and Wales rising, according to a report compiled by the Department
for Education and leaked yesterday to a Labour MP.
The report, drawn up by the Education Settlement Working Group, a body
involving representatives of local education authorities and civil servants
from the education and environment departments, predicts that the number of
nursery and primary pupils will rise by 66,000 next year, while secondary
pupils will increase by 54,000.
This would lead to an estimated pupil-teacher ratio of 17.99 to one (up from
17.66:1 in 1992-93, and 17.44:1 in 1991-92). The extra teachers would be
needed to stop the ratio increasing.
Mr Stephen Byers, the MP who published the report, said: 'If the government
is serious about providing high standards in our schools, they must respond
in a positive way to this report. Failure to do so will condemn a whole
generation of school children to a sub-standard education.'
A demographic shift and increased staying-on rates among 16-year-olds who
might previously have left school and looked for work are blamed for the
increase in numbers.
Local-authority associations meet Mr John Gummer, the environment secretary,
today to negotiate levels of standard spending. They are likely to use the
estimates in calling for extra funds.
The report's publication follows a letter to Mr John Patten, the education
secretary, from Mr David Hart, general secretary of the National Association
of Head Teachers, which said that pupil-teacher ratios had risen to an
unacceptable level.
</TEXT>
