<HEADLINE>
FT  22 JUL 93 / World Trade News: Gatt in new study of banana regime
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By REUTER
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   GENEVA
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
DEVELOPING countries from rival groups of banana producers clashed yesterday
in the ruling council of the General Agreement on Tariffs and Trade over the
European Community's controversial banana import policies, Reuter reports
from Geneva.
The debate went on for three hours before being suspended until the next
session in September, according to trade officials. However, they said that
Gatt had now formed a panel to report on whether the EC's new regime, which,
like its predecessor, has also split the Community, violated international
fair trade rules.
Jamaica, a member of the Africa, Caribbean and Pacific (ACP) group of former
colonies of European states, appealed for rejection of an earlier panel
report which declared the EC's previous banana import regulations to be in
violation of Gatt rules. 'Its conclusions could destroy the future of 69
developing nation states,' said Jamaica's ambassador, Mr Richard Pierce.
Costa Rica argued for approval, speaking for five Latin American states
whose bananas are subject to heavy EC duties and import ceilings.
The EC blocked approval of the report last month, but has since introduced
new rules imposing a tariff quota of 2m tonnes a year on non-ACP imports.
Earlier, the council agreed to work for early admission of Saudi Arabia as a
full member after the kingdom's application won support from Middle East and
Asian states.
The latter argued that Saudi entry would help Gatt move towards bringing in
all the world's trading states.
