<HEADLINE>
FT  22 JUL 93 / Chinese slowdown to hit HK growth
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By SIMON HOLBERTON
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   HONG KONG
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
MOVES to damp economic activity in China will lop about 1 percentage point
off Hong Kong's economic growth next year, Mr Hamish Macleod, the colony's
financial secretary, said yesterday, Simon Holberton reports from Hong Kong.
He said he accepted predictions by private economic forecasters that the
colony's growth would be affected by the measures announced in China to deal
with overheating. However, he stood by his March budget forecast of 5.5 per
cent growth in gross domestic product for 1993. He would not make a 1994
prediction but most forecasters expect about 4.5 per cent.
He said he believed the Chinese authorities would be successful in cooling
economic growth on the mainland. 'When the centre (Beijing) makes it plain
that it has a policy priority, sends teams to the provinces, and shifts
people from their jobs I think it will be taken seriously.'
</TEXT>
