FT  22 JUL 93 / German money supply threatens franc
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PETER JOHN
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   LONDON
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
THE uncomfortably high German money supply figure added to concerns over the
prospects for the French franc yesterday, writes Peter John in London.
Economists feared that if Germany does not ease monetary policy soon France
will have to raise rates to support its currency, a possibility that had
been dismissed until yesterday. 'Tensions within the ERM mean that Germany
is obliged to pursue a monetary policy which is easier than is fully
appropriate under domestic inflationary conditions,' said Mr Thomas Mayer at
Goldman Sachs in Frankfurt yesterday. He pointed out that France is obliged
to keep interest rates higher than the fundamentals require.
The franc was marginally firmer at Ffr3.41.50 against the D-Mark, just over
1.5 centimes above its ERM floor. However, French government bond futures
went through a key support level to close more than half a percentage point
lower.
