<HEADLINE>
FT  22 JUL 93 / Poland's Dollars 12bn debt talks collapse
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ANTHONY ROBINSON
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
NEGOTIATIONS between Poland and its London Commercial Club creditors for a
reduction in Warsaw's Dollars 12.1bn bank debt were suspended indefinitely
yesterday,
The Polish side rejected the banks' proposals as 'not acceptable'. Mr
Krzysztof Krowacki, the chief negotiator, said: 'We did not expect such a
tough approach. The banks have been sending out signals that we would be
offered something serious. That is apparently not so.'
Poland is seeking an agreement for a reduction of its 1 debt to more than
300 commercial banks similar to the two-stage, 50 per cent debt reduction
agreed with the Paris Club on Dollars 33bn of official debt in April 1991.
In May Poland and the banks agreed to enter negotiations on the basis of
three principles which linked an eventual debt reduction agreement to
Poland's capacity to pay and its existing agreement with the Paris Club.
Mr Krowacki, who is being advised by Kidder Peabody, the US merchant bank
and the US law firm, White &amp; Case, said: 'If the banks come up with a
proposal in line with the three principles or are prepared to discuss our
proposals, we would return to the table immediately. But there are no plans
for this at present.'
No comment was available from the banks last night.
