<HEADLINE>
FT  22 JUL 93 / Bankers brush aside fears over derivatives market
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By LAURIE MORSE and TRACY CORRIGAN
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
A GROUP of the world's top bankers has brushed aside fears that the Dollars
4,000bn (Pounds 2,600bn) derivatives market threatens the international
banking system.
The Group of Thirty, a Washington-based think-tank chaired by Mr Paul
Volcker, former head of the US Federal Reserve, concludes in a report
published yesterday that no new regulations are required. However, it says
market participants should implement stricter internal controls.
The long-awaited recommendations on these sophisticated financial
instruments contrast sharply with concerns voiced recently by Mr William
McDonough, new chairman of the New York Fed, and with warnings last year by
his predecessor, Mr Gerald Corrigan, that the market might be running out of
control.
Derivatives are instruments, such as futures, options and swaps, whose value
is based on an underlying cash market in stocks, currencies, interest rates
or commodities.
To their supporters, they have brought greater flexibility to the management
of financial risks of companies, investors, government agencies and others.
To their critics, they have created complex risks that few users and traders
know how to handle.
The G30 concedes the instruments are complicated but rules out fresh
regulatory initiatives. It calls for a deeper understanding of derivatives
and says senior management should closely monitor the use of such
instruments. It argues that risk is diminished if users observe strict
internal controls.
Mr Volcker, in a foreword to the report, says: 'The critically important
contribution of this study has been to define a set of sound risk management
practices for dealers and end users.' The G30 report concurs with recent
reviews of derivatives by the Bank of England and the Bank for International
Settlements.
A Bank of England official said the G30 report seemed 'in keeping' with its
own derivatives report issued in April.
Many of the group's findings - that public disclosure of derivatives
exposures is inadequate; that wider acceptance of multi-product netting
agreements is needed; and that accounting practices for derivatives must be
standardised - are not new.
The report sidesteps the controversial issue of capital adequacy that
underlies the unease about derivatives trading.
Sir Dennis Weatherstone, chairman of investment bank JP Morgan and leader of
the G30 study group on derivatives, said the main problem facing the
derivatives industry had been a lack of understanding.
'We have made substantial progress in this area,' said Sir Dennis.
Easy option or unnecessary risk, Page 19
G30 sets new benchmark for derivatives industry, Page 27
</TEXT>
<XX>
Countries:-
</XX>
<CN>USZ  United States of America.
</CN>
