<HEADLINE>
FT  22 JUL 93 / Clarke hails 'all-round' upturn: Chancellor renews warning
that tax rises may be needed to cut deficit
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PETER NORMAN and EMMA TUCKER
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
BRITAIN is experiencing an 'all-round recovery' that was 'good and balanced
so far', Mr Kenneth Clarke, the chancellor, said yesterday as new figures
confirmed rising business activity in Britain's high streets and a narrowing
trade gap.
But Mr Clarke warned that growth this year would not suffice to cut the
budget deficit as much as needed.
He said that 'further government action' might be necessary in another
indication that the government is considering raising taxes while limiting
public expenditure in its first unified Budget in November.
In a two-hour session before the Commons Treasury and Civil Service
committee, Mr Clarke said the size of the deficit - estimated by the
Treasury in March at Pounds 50bn in 1993-94 - was 'the biggest single thing'
that he had to tackle.
Unless the deficit was reduced, recovery would be constrained and it might
be difficult to keep interest rates down, he said.
The chancellor disclosed that the Budget would be on November 30, but told
the committee he had not yet started to think about its specific contents.
However, he did say the Conservative party preferred to have indirect
taxation take a bigger share of the tax burden than direct taxes.
Mr Clarke was careful not to sound euphoric about Britain's present economic
performance, at one point describing the recovery as 'incipient'. But his
testimony to the committee, just two months after he moved into Number 11
Downing Street, came at the end of a fortnight of favourable economic
indicators and shortly before provisional figures tomorrow are expected to
show good growth in gross domestic product in the second quarter.
Figures yesterday showing a surprisingly strong jump in retail sales and
strong export growth added to evidence that the UK recovery is not as
vulnerable as initially expected. Seasonally adjusted retail sales volumes
rose 1.3 per cent in June for a 3.9 per cent increase on the corresponding
month last year, the Central Statistical Office reported.
Other official figures showed that the value of exports to countries outside
the European Community jumped to their highest ever levels last month,
reducing the non-EC trade deficit to Pounds 613m, its narrowest since July
1991.
The figures added to sterling's recent strength, with the pound closing in
London  3/4 of a pfennig higher against the D-Mark at DM2.5725. Against the
dollar it was just over a cent higher at Dollars 1.5145, with little change
against either currency in New York.
Several MPs asked Mr Clarke if he was worried that sterling's recent rise
would hurt recovery. But the chancellor said the pound's rise since he took
office had been 'modest' and reflected 'underlying economic reality' such as
the healthier performance of the economy.
Mr Clarke said inflationary pressures in Britain were weak but pointed out
that forecasters envisaged inflation rising by the end of the year.
Yesterday's economic news failed to enthuse the stock market, partly because
investors saw less chance of an early interest rate cut. The FTSE 100 share
index dropped 9.8 to 2814.1.
