<HEADLINE>
FT  21 JUL 93 / London Stock Exchange: Reuters gains
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JOEL KIBAZO, CHRISTOPHER PRICE and CHRISTINE BUCKLEY
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
A strong recommendation for Reuters from Lehman Brothers ensured that the
shares remained in positive territory, adding 8 at 1392p, in a poor day in
the market.
Mr Alastair Smellie at the US investment bank believes that Reuters'
'unrivalled market penetration, its quality and visibility of earnings,
enormous financial strength and accelerating growth prospects more than
justify its current premium rating'. He predicted that the stock would rise
to 1600p within the next year. The company reports interim figures next
week.
Chemicals manufacturer BOC Group rose 6 to 655p as Hoare Govett recommended
the stock. The broker said the shares have underperformed by 20 per cent
this year and look good value. At the same time, Hoare downgraded Laporte
from Pounds 114m to Pounds 110m for this year, citing tough trading
conditions. The shares fell 17 to 578p.
Results from SmithKline Beecham came in at the top end of market forecasts,
helping the shares put on 3 at 419p. Pre-tax profits grew 15 per cent to
Pounds 601m from Pounds 521m. Mr Robert Bauman, the chief executive, said
the group's performance was satisfactory, but he warned of an increasing
degree of uncertainty in the drugs sector due to economic and regulatory
pressures.
Meanwhile, selected drugs stocks bounced from their recent weakness as
investors looked for bargains. Wellcome advanced 17 to 621p and Glaxo 8 to
531p.
Calm came to the second day's trading in the new BT partly-paid shares and
they closed a halfpenny ahead at 168 1/2 p. Turnover was 41m, against
Monday's 187m, as the profit-takers faded and the stock settled into a
narrow trading range. BT ordinary were unchanged at 413 1/2 p.
Second line hotel issues, battered in recent sessions following the
suspension of Resort Hotels, staged a modest rally, although confidence in
the UK economic recovery remained uncertain. Stakis, helped by reinforced
positive stances from Hoare Govett and Smith New Court, firmed 3 to 55p in
volume of 1.2m. Friendly Hotels moved up 4 to 202p.
British Aerospace retreated 18 to 400p amid talk of an oversupply of defence
equipment on the market and further concern about the financing of BAe's
planned Pounds 250m regional jets joint venture with Taiwan. However, the
company's chairman said he was confident that the financing problems would
be solved shortly.
Among motor issues, GKN added 8 at 461p and T&amp;N improved 4 to 194p, with
agency broker Henderson Crosthwaite said to have been the day's big shoppers
with a view that next month's UK new car registrations should benefit both
component suppliers.
Profit-taking left Siebe 5 lighter at 492p. Strong demand for Vosper
Thornycroft following a recent visit from institutions saw the shares rise
16 to 629p. A stock shortage continued in VSEL, which climbed 15 to 863p. A
squeeze also drove Hunting 9 ahead to 236p. Bargain hunters for Meggitt
helped to reverse the recent decline in the stock. The shares hardened 3 to
105p.
The first day of dealings in engineering group Quadramatic cheered the
market. Having made its debut at 123p, the stock ended 5 higher at 128p.
In the transport sector, US selling continued in Tiphook, sending the stock
further into retreat following last week's figures which revealed a loss.
The shares closed 17 lower at 213p, but after having been lifted off the
bottom by bargain hunters.
An announcement from Ocean Group that it had won a multi-million-pound
six-year contract from Procter and Gamble for the distribution of P&amp;G's
detergents in Spain coincided with news that it is to invest Pounds 18m in
constructing an automated distribution centre in that country. The shares
gained 4 at 292p.
A technical boost buoyed Campari, the sporting clothes company. Some demand
and a dearth of sellers pushed it up 5 to 138p.
Reports that National Westminster Bank had collected details of customers'
political affiliations overhung the banking sector. NatWest dropped 15 to
491p, with talk that it may soon call on investors for cash also doing the
rounds. Lloyds receded 9 to 579p, while Barclays gave up 14 to 478p.
</TEXT>
