<HEADLINE>
FT  21 JUL 93 / London Stock Exchange: Equity futures and options trading
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By CHRISTINE BUCKLEY
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
A QUIET morning proved to be the calm before the storm in stock index
futures after gloomy signs for the US economy tested investors' nerves,
Christine Buckley writes.
Virtually ignoring the mid-morning UK money supply figures, dealers reacted
actively to pessimistic remarks from the Federal Reserve on the US inflation
rate and sold the FT-SE 100 September contract down. Fears were further
fuelled by speculation over the possibility of an interest rate rise in the
US.
Such a violent reaction proved the poor underlying state of the futures
market, according to one trader, who did not expect much promise to be seen
before the August bank holiday. Some market watchers fear that the
underlying support level of 2,780 for the September contract may soon make
an appearance in trading.
The contract greeted the day at 2,858 and enjoyed a brief spell at 2,863
before slipping back. The Fed's remarks pushed it to the day's low of 2,820
at about 3.30pm. A slight rally left it closing at 2,824 after 9,933
contracts traded. It trailed its fair value premium to cash by 1.9 points.
Traded options had a lacklustre day with trade edging up only slightly to
20,879 lots from Monday's total. The FT-SE 100 option took the lion's share,
at 8,493 contracts. Of stock options, only British Airways deals exceeded
1,000 lots, reaching 1,261.
