<HEADLINE>
FT  21 JUL 93 / International Company News: Europe recession hits Honeywell
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By LOUISE KEHOE
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   SAN FRANCISCO
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
HONEYWELL, the US electronic control systems group, reported a drop in net
income and revenues for the second quarter.
Sales were Dollars 1.45bn, down from Dollars 1.49bn in the same period last
year. Net income was Dollars 71.4m, or 53 cents a share, including an
after-tax gain of Dollars 13.9m, or 10 cents, from the settlement of a
lawsuit with Unisys. The gain was offset by special charges of Dollars 13.3m
after taxes to improve productiv-ity.
In the same period last year, net income was Dollars 81.8m, or 58 cents a
share, including Dollars 7.4m, or 6 cents, after-tax from litigation
settlements.
Second-quarter operating profit, excluding special charges, was Dollars
131.7m, compared with Dollars 152.3m last year.
'We are delivering solid financial performance in the face of very difficult
business conditions worldwide,' said Mr Michael Bonsignore, chairman and
chief executive.
In addition to a cyclical decline in the commercial aviation industry, the
company's difficulties have been compounded by the deepening recession in
Europe, especially in Germany, he added.
'Despite the difficult environment, we expanded research and development
investment by 15 per cent,' Mr Bonsignore said. During the quarter,
Honeywell purchased Dollars 64m in shares as part of its five-year, Dollars
600m share buy-back programme.
Honeywell's space and aviation business was down sharply in the quarter,
with operating profit of Dollars 48.5m on sales of Dollars 424.7m, compared
with an operating profit of Dollars 61.4m on sales of Dollars 460.9m in the
same period last year.
First-half income was Dollars 128.7m, or 95 cents a share, against Dollars
50.7m, or 36 cents, last year. Sales were Dollars 2.89bn, against Dollars
2.97bn a year earlier.
</TEXT>
