<HEADLINE>
FT  21 JUL 93 / International Company News: Philip Morris falls 22% as
cigarette profits slump
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By MARTIN DICKSON
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   NEW YORK
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
PHILIP Morris, the US food and tobacco group, yesterday announced a 22 per
cent drop in second-quarter net earnings as its US cigarette profits slumped
following April's sharp cut in the price of its Marlboro brand.
Net earnings were Dollars 1.1bn, or Dollars 1.20 a share, down from Dollars
1.35bn, or Dollars 1.48, in the same period of last year on revenues which
rose 4.2 per cent to Dollars 15.79bn.
Mr Michael Miles, chairman, said that the group's consumer businesses other
than US tobacco were continuing to enjoy solid profits group, up 13.3 per
cent for the quarter.
The company's announcement on April 2 that it would not make any US premium
brand cigarette price increases, and was cutting the price of Marlboro, led
to a reduction in wholesale inventories.
This meant a 21.5 per cent decline in second-quarter US cigarette volume to
47.5bn units. Philip Morris said that primarily due to this reduced volume,
and increased marketing expenses associated with the price cuts,
second-quarter operating income for domestic tobacco was down 53.1 per cent
at Dollars 684m.
However, market share growth in the premium segment and in discount sales
meant Philip Morris's retail share of the US tobacco market reached a record
43.6 per cent in the quarter.
The pricing strategy for premium products, and improved prices on discount
products, 'allow for future profits growth off the newly established base,'
the company said.
International tobacco operations saw operating income rise 15.6 per cent to
Dollars 577m on revenues 25 per cent ahead at Dollars 4bn. Marlboro's
international sales volume rose 2.2 per cent to 58.7bn units.
North American food operations had operating income 9.9 per cent higher at
Dollars 667m, while revenues rose 1.6 per cent to Dollars 5.4bn.
International food produced income of Dollars 269m, up 13 per cent, on
revenues 19.9 per cent ahead at Dollars 2.5bn, due primarily to acquisitions
and growth in confectionery, partly offset by currency movements.
Its Miller brewing company made Dollars 140m, up 21.7 per cent, on revenues
1.1 per cent higher at Dollars 1.2bn.
For the half year, the group reported net earnings of Dollars 2.27bn, or
Dollars 2.58, compared with Dollars 2.45bn, or Dollars 2.68, in 1992.
</TEXT>
