<HEADLINE>
FT  21 JUL 93 / Loan quality boosts Citicorp
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By RICHARD WATERS
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   NEW YORK
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
A SHARP drop in write-offs on property and commercial loans and a fall in
loan-loss provisions fuelled a profits recovery at Citicorp, the US's
largest banking group, in the second three months of the year.
The group's results echoed the improvement in credit quality reported by
other US banks in recent days, due to firmer property prices and the first
clear signs that the patchy US economic recovery is feeding through to
banks' customers.
Record income from trading in the foreign exchange and securities markets
also lifted Citicorp's after-tax profits, which reached Dollars 446m (Pounds
296m), up from Dollars 143m in the same period in 1992.
Write-offs on property and commercial loans at the banking group fell to
Dollars 297m, down from Dollars 380m in the first quarter and well below the
peak of Dollars 792m in the last quarter of 1991.
Lower losses on north American commercial property were behind the
improvement: credit losses dropped from Dollars 527m in the second quarter
of 1992 to Dollars 251m. Provisions for commercial and property loan losses
made during the quarter were Dollars 273m, down from Dollars 583m a year
before.
Income from trading in financial markets soared to Dollars 572m, from
Dollars 314m a year earlier, topping the quarterly record for a US bank set
by JP Morgan only a week ago with Dollars 431m. Some Dollars 352m (up from
Dollars 193m) came from foreign exchange.
Leaving aside the lower credit charges and gains from trading, profits
remained sluggish, contributing to a Dollars  1/4 decline in the group's
share price to Dollars 31 3/4 by close. Mr John Reed, chairman, said revenue
growth had been held back by 'troubled economies in the developed world',
but that developing countries had grown strongly.
Earnings per share in the second quarter reached 82 cents, up from 25 cents.
For the first half net income was Dollars 1.1bn, or Dollars 2.06 a share,
compared with Dollars 326m, or Dollars 0.61 a share, in the first six months
of 1992, after an accounting change. The group's key tier one capital ratio
rose to 5.7 per cent from 5.3 per cent at the end of March.
US bank results, Page 24
</TEXT>
