<HEADLINE>
FT  21 JUL 93 / Philip Morris extends price cut to premium cigarettes
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By MARTIN DICKSON
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   NEW YORK
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
PHILIP Morris, which shocked the US tobacco industry in April by temporarily
slashing the price of its Marlboro cigarettes, yesterday made the 20 per
cent price cut permanent and extended it to other premium brands, including
Virginia Slims and Benson &amp; Hedges.
The move confirms that the price of Marlboro, the best-selling cigarette in
the US, was out of line with cheap discount products before the cut on April
2, known as 'Marlboro Friday'.
Philip Morris said that the price cut had reversed Marlboro's slide in
market share. Its US tobacco profits have, however, been hit hard by the
cuts.
The company, which also makes food and drink products, yesterday announced
second quarter earnings of Dollars 1.1bn (Pounds 730m), down 22.2 per cent.
The results and its price action had been expected on Wall Street and its
shares closed up Dollars  1/4 at Dollars 48 1/2 .
The discount sector, which consists of cheap branded goods and unbranded
generic cigarettes, has grown rapidly in recent years at the expense of
premium brands and now accounts for 40 per cent of the US market. Philip
Morris, one of the largest companies in the discount market, also announced
pricing changes in this area.
It said it would push up the price of its most heavily discounted brands and
move less heavily discounted brands down to that level, creating a two-tier
price structure rather than the present three tiers. None of the cuts
affects markets outside the US.
Other manufacturers seem bound to follow the premium price cuts but may not
raise the price of deeply discounted brands. RJ Reynolds, the other leading
US tobacco company, said it would match Philip Morris' action at both ends
of the market.
Philip Morris said Marlboro's market share, which bottomed out at less than
22 per cent in March after eight months of decline, had risen to 22.6 per
cent in May, according to Nielsen, the market research company. Its own data
suggested the July share might rise to 24 per cent. Growth had been coming
at the expense of both premium brands and discount cigarettes.
Philip Morris added that the price changes would not affect the forecast
made in April of operating earnings from its US tobacco business falling by
as much as 40 per cent this year.
Lex, Page 18
Results, Page 23
</TEXT>
