<HEADLINE>
FT  21 JUL 93 / The Lex Column: Philip Morris
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
The noxious smoke which Philip Morris blew over other consumer products
companies when it first cut the price of Marlboro cigarettes grew thicker
yesterday. Its decision to make the price cuts permanent provoked fresh
fears about brand values.
The UK market, though, appears to have particular trouble peering through
the smog. It knocked the shares of both Unilever and Cadbury-Schweppes,
which are in wholly unrelated businesses, while leaving those of tobacco
giant, BAT Industries, untouched. This may owe something to Philip Morris's
simultaneous decision to raise the price of its discount cigarettes. The
market's reaction seems perverse nonetheless.
