<HEADLINE>
FT  21 JUL 93 / The Lex Column: UK economy
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
After last week's good news on industrial production and unemployment, the
deceleration of M4 money supply growth is disconcerting. But the slippage
may not be as serious for recovery as it looks. It reflects a shift in
corporate financing habits, whereby bank debt is being securitised through
the issue of new equity capital or fixed-rate bonds. June alone saw
companies raising some Pounds 3.5bn in the equity market, thanks partly to
the flurry of rights issues from the property sector.
Such balance sheet restructuring bodes well for future economic activity,
especially since consumers show signs of being prepared to borrow again. The
recovery may not be running away with itself, but it is not exactly
faltering either.
</TEXT>
