<HEADLINE>
FT  21 JUL 93 / British Gas to freeze prices for householders: Move comes a
week before MMC delivers verdict
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By DEBORAH HARGREAVES
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
BRITISH GAS will freeze prices for its 18m household customers this year
even though the formula which governs its domestic prices shows room for a 1
per cent increase.
Mr Norman Blacker, managing director of British Gas's UK gas business, said
the company would await the outcome of the Monopolies and Mergers Commission
inquiry into the gas industry before deciding the next move on prices. The
commission's verdict is due to be delivered at the end of next week and
British Gas does not want to become involved in a price wrangle before that.
Mr Ian Powe, director of the Gas Consumers' Council, said: 'Only British Gas
would boast about holding monopoly prices steady when the MMC is within a
week of delivering its report. Any other decision would have been
universally condemned.' A complex formula keeps gas price rises 5 percentage
points below the rate of inflation. This would suggest a price cut, but
British Gas said the other part of the formula, which is based on North Sea
gas and other energy prices, allowed the company to raise prices by 1 per
cent.
Sir James McKinnon, director general of Ofgas, the regulator, said the 1 per
cent price increase would have amounted to less than  1/2 p a therm, which
probably would have been swallowed up in administrative costs.
British Gas said it was unlikely to change its prices before the end of the
year. The company normally reviews prices in April and October.
British Gas also published the results of a study by Mori and Gallup
researchers which found that consumers were opposed to standards of service
being jeopardised by price cuts. The company was forced by its regulator to
cut prices twice last year. Ofgas said the company should have known without
commissioning a survey that customers were very satisfied with the service
package conceived by the regulator and agreed by British Gas.
Sir James said: 'Value for money is a combination of price and standards of
service. British Gas cannot now trade service standards at the expense of
price.'
The survey found that 93 per cent of customers oppose cutting spending on
providing instant responses to gas leaks. It found that consumers would be
prepared to pay more to maintain British Gas's responsibilities to the
community as a whole.
British Gas said that a third of its industrial market was supplied by
competitors who served 34 per cent of industrial users - up from 28 per cent
at the end of last year. Rivals had also captured 15 per cent of sales in
the commercial market, which was opened to competition last year.
</TEXT>
