<HEADLINE>
FT  21 JUL 93 / Arts: Today's Television
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By CHRISTOPHER DUNKLEY
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Having suffered periodic back pain for 20 years I shall watch Doc Martin's
Casebook (7.30 BBC1) with fascination and scepticism. Doctors stand in
relation to back pain as clergymen do to god: it is all faith and mumbo
jumbo. They know nothing for sure, work entirely in the dark, and success
(rare) is a matter of pure chance.
If we cannot have another British police series as good as Between The
Lines, and the Americans are producing nothing to compare with Kojak or Hill
Street Blues, I suppose third best - an Australian series - will just have
to do. Presumably the broadcasters feel that in Police Rescue they do at
least speak English, or a close approximation. In today's episode there is
derring-do on a skyscraper and a crane.
The last of Channel 4's tribute to the late Juris Podnieks, Camera Of
Courage, deals with events in Latvia and Armenia just prior to the collapse
of the Soviet Union (9.00). BBC2's season of repeats of The Wednesday Play
from the 1960s offers an early Dennis Potter: 'Where The Buffalo Roam',
starring Hywel Bennett as a retarded Welsh teenager (9.00).
</TEXT>
