<HEADLINE>
FT  21 JUL 93 / Parliament and Politics: Government proposals in latest
'assualt' on red tape
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
Among proposals in the government's latest 'assault' on red tape are:
Enforcement agencies
Establish a code of conduct for enforcement agencies, requiring each of them
to publish their own codes for promoting openness, courtesy, helpfulness,
dealing with complaints and the giving of value for money.
Oil and gas
Streamline approval procedures for oil and gas field development consents.
Small businesses
Relax the statutory requirement for audit on 'certain small companies'.
Introduce a new 'small business litmus test' to be satisfied before new
regulations are imposed.
Health
Examine statutory sick pay regulations to simplify administration of the
scheme and reduce 'unnecessary' burdens on business.
Consumers
Simplify consumer credit legislation.
Transport
Reform regulation of taxis and minicabs.
Change the operator licensing regime for heavy goods vehicles and buses.
Local controls
'Streamline' water pollution and air emission controls.
Some proposals have already been announced by departments. None are
detailed, and many are only 'possibilities' pending further review.
</TEXT>
