<HEADLINE>
FT  21 JUL 93 / Parliament and Politics: Lilley warns on benefits spending
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By IVOR OWEN, Parliamentary Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
MR Peter Lilley, social security secretary, told the Commons last night
there could be no escape from 'structural reform' of the benefits system.
He insisted that it was necessary both to contain the growth of the Pounds
80bn social security budget and to ensure that the money was spent to best
effect.
The government secured a majority of 44 (312-268) to defeat a Labour motion
accusing it of seeking to dismantle the welfare state.
Mr Lilley said the underlying position of social security spending
outstripping national income could not be sustained indefinitely.
Accepting the need for a 'considered look' at the social security budget, Mr
Donald Dewar, shadow social security secretary, warned that Labour would
battle against short-term reforms stemming from the Treasury's 'crisis
management demands'.
Mr Lilley identified three main sources of expenditure - invalidity and
related benefits, lone parents and housing benefit - for the projected
growth in social security provision to the end of the century.
Mr Lilley accepted that growth in lone parenthood - up from 570,000 in 1971
to 1.3m in 1991 - was not likely to be checked primarily by changes in the
benefit system.
The availability of housing was a significant factor, he said, and welcomed
a recent statement by Mr David Blunkett, shadow health secretary, calling
for positive housing policies which did not encourage the belief that having
a baby was the only way to a home.
</TEXT>
