<HEADLINE>
FT  21 JUL 93 / Parliament and Politics: Labour calls for end to BT curb
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ANDREW ADONIS
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
LABOUR yesterday called for an end to the ban on British Telecommunications
providing entertainment services in return for its agreement to reduce
'drastically' the number of people without a phone, Andrew Adonis writes.
Mr Robin Cook, shadow trade and industry secretary, said the 10-year ban -
imposed by the government two years ago to encourage cable TV companies to
build local phone and cable TV networks - was 'grossly unfair'.
He said: 'Its only benefit is to BT's international rivals. North American
telecoms companies have major stakes in 93 per cent of cable TV operators.
'It is a disincentive to BT to invest in the UK, forcing it to spend its
money abroad,' he added, pointing to BT's recent Dollars 4.3bn investment in
MCI, the second-largest US operator.
BT welcomed Labour's support for an end to the entertainment ban, which it
claims is anti-competitive and a hindrance to its capacity to finance an
advanced fibre-optic network within local exchanges, but it refused to
concede the need for further reductions in connection charges to increase
lines.
