<HEADLINE>
FT  21 JUL 93 / Parliament and Politics: Agencies to set codes of conduct
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ANDREW ADONIS
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
GOVERNMENT enforcement agencies will be obliged to publish codes of conduct
by next January, under proposals produced by the the government's 'red tape'
review.
The agencies - public bodies including the Civil Aviation Authority, the
Pollution Inspectorate and the Health and Safety Executive - will be
required to produce codes covering standards, complaints procedures, value
for money, and 'courtesy and helpfulness'.
The code is one of the few definite new proposals in yesterday's 'progress
report' by the deregulation team at the Department of Trade and Industry,
following a meeting of ministers with the prime minister and Lord Sainsbury,
the government's deregulation adviser.
Mr Tim Sainsbury, standing in for Mr Michael Heseltine, trade and industry
secretary, said an 'important' Deregulation Bill was under consideration,
but he refused to disclose the matters it would cover and said its
introduction would only come 'as soon as parliamentary time permits'.
Mr Sainsbury - Lord Sainsbury's brother - said: 'Deregulation is a vital
element in helping to improve the competitiveness of British industry:
reviews of departments' regulations are now yielding major prospects for
change.'
Proposals under consideration include the ending of remaining restrictions
on weekday shop opening in England and Wales; a review of key areas of food
law including hygiene, labelling and enforcement; a green paper on the
regulation of taxis and minicabs; and a change in the licensing regime for
heavy goods vehicles and buses.
The Department of Social Security and Inland Revenue will take a 'fresh
look' at rules governing the designation of people as self-employed, and the
DSS will review the statutory sick pay regime.
Mr Peter Lilley, social security secretary, has set up a working group to
look at the burden of different definitions of earning for tax and national
insurance purposes.
Editorial Comment and Observer, Page 17
</TEXT>
