THE LABOUR party yesterday called for an end to the ban on British
Telecommunications providing entertainment services in return for its
agreement to reduce 'drastically' the number of people without a phone.
Mr Robin Cook, shadow trade and industry secretary, said the 10-year ban -
imposed by the government two years ago to encourage cable TV companies to
build local phone and cable TV networks - was 'grossly unfair'.
He said: 'Its only benefit is to BT's international rivals. North American
telecoms companies have major stakes in 93 per cent of cable TV operators.
