<HEADLINE>
FT  21 JUL 93 / SIB orders building society to check advice
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By NORMA COHEN
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
NORTH of England Building Society, the UK's 20th largest society, has been
ordered by regulators to contact 600 customers who may have been misled when
sold pensions or investment products.
The Securities and Investments Board, which regulates the society, conducted
an inspection visit last October.
The Department of Social Security has asked regulators overseeing the sale
of personal pensions to ensure that they are not sold to those for whom they
are inappropriate. The board, along with Lautro and Fimbra, the
self-regulatory organisations for life insurers and independent financial
advisers respectively, had told sales agents not to encourage members of
occupational schemes to transfer to personal pensions.
The board, which has been criticised by the retail financial services
industry for being less rigorous a regulator than the self-regulatory
bodies, has stepped up its reviews of sales tactics. Recently, Barclays Bank
and National Westminster Bank, both regulated by SIB, have said they will
stop accepting pensions transfers.
The board's review at North of England raised questions about the quality of
advice given to those who had transferred out of their existing pension
arrangements and those who had purchased so-called single premium
with-profits bonds.
Regulators had been concerned that with-profits bonds had been sold as
high-yielding alternatives to building society deposit accounts and that
customers did not understand the heavy penalties for early withdrawal.
The society said SIB had ordered it to offer all 600 customers the chance to
have their cases reviewed by an separate independent financial adviser and
make restitution where necessary. So far, 163 have requested advice.
North of England has announced it will no longer be an independent financial
adviser and said it would sell only the products of General Accident Company
from September 1.
It added: 'We felt the cost of compliance for an independent financial
adviser was too great for a building society of our size,' it said.
</TEXT>
