<HEADLINE>
FT  21 JUL 93 / Police launch campaign against Sheehy changes
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ALAN PIKE, Social Affairs Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
POLICE OFFICERS staged the biggest demonstration in their history last night
in protest against the Sheehy committee's recommendations for radical
changes in pay and conditions.
More than 20,000 officers from throughout the UK filled London's Wembley
Arena and overflow halls. They launched a campaign to force the government
to abandon the recommendations, which include fixed-term contracts and
performance-related pay.
Police officers are banned by law from taking strike action, and last
night's exceptional demonstration was the most dramatic form of public
opposition to the proposals open to them. But Mr Alan Eastwood, chairman of
the Police Federation, warned that the rally was 'only the very small
beginning of our struggle' to defeat Sheehy. It marked the start of a
'campaign to save the service from the disaster of this report'.
The rally was organised by the federation, which represents officers up to
the rank of chief inspector, and the Superintendents' Association. Mr
Richard Wells, chief constable of South Yorkshire, said that the Sheehy
committee had viewed the police service through 'tight, prejudiced, narrow
fiscal windows'. Officers felt sick with worry over their own futures and
that of the service, he added.
Mr Michael Howard, home secretary, is holding consultations on the
recommendations until September, and has stressed that he has not yet
reached conclusions on any of them. Police reform and the fight against
crime have become high-profile political questions for the government. It is
due to legislate on proposals to make police authorities more businesslike
and on those aspects of Sheehy accepted by the government in the next
parliamentary session.
Last night's rally was addressed by Mr Tony Blair, shadow home secretary,
and Mr Robert Maclennan, Liberal Democrat home affairs spokesman. Mr
Maclennan received a standing ovation for a speech in which he described the
Sheehy report as a malevolent exercise whose primary purpose was to cut the
cost of policing rather than improve it.
Mr Blair said the test of police reforms must be whether they helped cut
crime rather than help the Treasury to cut corners.
</TEXT>
