<HEADLINE>
FT  21 JUL 93 / CAA raps government stance on Dan-Air
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By DANIEL GREEN
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE GOVERNMENT damaged the UK's ability to stop anti-competitive airline
mergers in the European Community by allowing British Airways to take over
its rival Dan-Air last year, Mr Christopher Chataway, chairman of the Civil
Aviation Authority, said yesterday.
Mr Chataway, a former Conservative minister, said the deal should have been
referred to the Monopolies and Mergers Commission. He added: 'The approval
will not make it easier for the UK to argue for a strong competition policy
within the EC.'
BA said yesterday: 'If the merger had not been approved when it was Dan-Air
would have disappeared overnight. We do not believe refusing this merger
would have been in the best interests of the travelling public, Dan-Air or
its staff.'
The Department of Trade and Industry said ministers had noted 'competition
concerns' at the time but that 'factors in the public interest' won the day.
Mr Chataway, presenting the CAA's annual report, also warned the Treasury
that cutting the CAA's borrowing powers would hit investment in air traffic
control and could increase delays to passengers in the UK's crowded
airports.
As a public body the CAA borrows from the Treasury. It borrowed Pounds 56m
last year, below its ceiling of Pounds 65.5m, and fears that the ceiling
will be reduced as a result.
'It is absolutely essential that we are able to borrow significantly. If we
don't, we can easily see a return to the delays of the late 1980s,' said Mr
Chataway.
The CAA annual report says that improvements in air traffic control led last
year to a sharp fall in airport waiting times.
Average delays on outbound flights from UK airports in May and June this
year were just seven minutes, compared with 14 minutes in May and June 1992.
The average delay on domestic flights in the same period was also seven
minutes - down from 20 minutes.
Early evening UK-bound flights from Belgium and Germany were subject to
delays of up to two hours early last year.
This had been cut to 30 minutes.
Mr Chataway added that the single market had heightened concern about the
charges made to cover the costs of safety regulations in the EC. It was only
in the UK that the full costs were recovered from the industry.
He added: 'To avoid damaging distortions, we must press for early
implementation of a common funding policy throughout the EC for safety
regulation.'
</TEXT>
