<HEADLINE>
FT  21 JUL 93 / Floods continue to threaten Midwest towns
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By REUTER
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   ST LOUIS
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
THE Mississippi threatened more towns and farmland in Illinois and Missouri
yesterday as the swollen river pushed relentlessly south, Reuter reports
from St Louis.
Prison officials in Chester, Illinois, ordered a heightened state of alert
as they planned to move inmates in low-lying cells to higher ground.
At St Genevieve, Missouri, volunteers fought to keep a sandbag levee from
crumbling. A city spokeswoman said that unless there was a surge of one inch
'we should be okay', as the crest approached the town later in the day.
The floods have caused an estimated Dollars 10bn (Pounds 6.6bn) in damage.
In Washington a congressional committee approved Dollars 3bn in emergency
aid for the flood zone yesterday as some legislators predicted Congress
might have to triple that amount eventually.
The army's Corps of Engineers said the river had not fallen much at St Louis
and would begin rising slightly again.
The floods in river valleys and rain-soaked farm fields have persisted for
more than a month in nine Midwestern states, killing as many as 31 people
and driving at least 30,000 people from their homes.
The misery spread to parts of Kansas yesterday where evacuations were under
way along the Kansas river following heavy rainfall. Officials in
Leavenworth County, north of Kansas City, warned residents that water being
released from two reservoirs farther west in the state would cause
additional flooding.
The volume of the task facing clean-up crews was becoming clearer. Crews
would face a smelly, difficult and dangerous job once the floodwaters
receded, experts on flooding said.
The overwhelming stench of spilt diesel fuel, rotting algae and animal
carcasses will hamper their effort, as will a thick layer of mud, rusting
appliances and other detritus swept up by the waters and dumped on the
flood-plain.
Petroleum products, agricultural pesticides and fertilisers, human and
animal waste and tonnes of silt have been swept into the river, along with
uprooted trees.
</TEXT>
