<HEADLINE>
FT  21 JUL 93 / Fall in ads for top jobs bottoms out
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By DIANE SUMMERS, Labour Staff
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
A FOUR-YEAR decline in the number of jobs for executives advertised in
national newspapers has bottomed out, according to figures released by the
MSL consultancy today.
For the second consecutive quarter recruitment figures stabilised, although
demand was still more than 2 1/2 times below the mid-1980s peak, the figures
show.
Mr Garry Long, MSL chief executive, said: 'The last time we saw this kind of
result was in early 1981 as that recession was ending. Three consecutive
quarters of stable results preceded the 1980s boom.'
MSL said its analysis of more than 4,000 executive jobs advertised showed
strong regional variations. There was more activity in London and the
south-east in the second quarter of this year than at any time since early
1991 - the region now accounts for 70 per cent of executive jobs advertised
in the UK.
Yorkshire and Humberside also saw increases in advertising in the second
quarter, but declines were registered elsewhere, apart from the north-west
and Scotland, which have been relatively stable.
The figures illustrated large differences between sectors. High-technology
recruitment was up 36 per cent between the first and second quarters of 1993
and 23 per cent up over the year. Retailing rose by 28 per cent and was up
10 per cent from a year previously.
Recruitment of executives in the food, drink and tobacco sector fell 9 per
cent from the previous quarter but was up 20 per cent on last year.
Energy-related industries had the largest fall over the year - down by more
than a third.
Marketing and sales had the strongest increase - up 40 per cent on the year
and 23 per cent between the first and second quarters. Accounting/ finance
and personnel had sharp rises in the first quarter, but fell in the second
by 8 per cent and 21 per cent respectively.
</TEXT>
