<HEADLINE>
FT  21 JUL 93 / Sanctions threat to China over missiles
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
THE Clinton administration, which two months ago renewed favourable trade
benefits for China, has threatened to impose economic sanctions on Beijing
if it ships missiles to Pakistan in defiance of an international agreement,
Agencies report from Washington.
The issue - following strong evidence that China is shipping M-11 missile
technology to Pakistan - will be raised by Mr Warren Christopher, US
secretary of state, when he meets his Chinese counterpart, Mr Qian Qichen,
on Sunday in Singapore. Ms Lynn Davis, undersecretary of state and the
Clinton administration's chief arms negotiator, will also discuss the matter
in Beijing.
The 'effect of applicable US law would be made clear to China and that
includes the likelihood of sanctions under certain circumstances,' a State
Department spokesman said. He added that sanctions would be imposed once it
was determined that 'certain transshipments of items have occurred, and to
my knowledge we have not determined that'.
The US has been concerned about China's M-11 missile sales to Pakistan for
several years, arguing they violate the missile technology control regime
designed to stem the spread of ballistic missiles. China has said it
supplied short-range missiles to Pakistan without exceeding MTCR.
