FT  21 JUL 93 / Europe's trees take a beating
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By FRANCES WILLIAMS
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   GENEVA
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
The state of Europe's forests deteriorated again last year with nearly a
quarter of trees suffering defoliation of at least 25 per cent, according to
an annual survey by the European Commission and the United Nations Economic
Commission for Europe, writes Frances Williams in Geneva. Weather, insects,
fungi, forest fire, action of man, game and air pollution were all blamed,
but most countries said air pollution was a factor.
