<HEADLINE>
FT  20 JUL 93 / London Stock Exchange: Medeva shock
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JOEL KIBAZO, CHRISTOPHER PRICE and CHRISTINE BUCKLEY
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
A shock profits warning from Medeva sent shares in the group tumbling 100 to
116p, and did further damage to a drugs sector weak from recent adverse
comment. Turnover was a very heavy 28m shares, accounting for nearly 10 per
cent of the issued equity. The dramatic fall in the share price revealed
deeper worries in the market over the quality of the stock.
The company warned that problems at one of its US subsidiaries would mean
profits some Pounds 10m below market forecasts for this year. One
pharmaceuticals specialist commented: 'Medeva has always based its earnings
growth on its acquisitions and now one of those has gone wrong. The market
is worried that it could happen elsewhere.' There were also darker hints
that warnings of trading worries at the group had been circulating in the
market for some weeks, but had been firmly rejected by sources close to the
company.
</TEXT>
