<HEADLINE>
FT  20 JUL 93 / International Company News: Boost for Travelers' shares as
profits show advance
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By RICHARD WATERS
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
SHARES in Travelers, the US insurance group hampered by a Dollars 5bn
portfolio of property loans, jumped by Dollars 2 3/8 yesterday before
settling back to close at Dollars 31 3/8 , a rise on the day of Dollars 1
3/8 , on news that profits had advanced strongly in the second quarter of
the year. Operating profits reached Dollars 94m, compared with Dollars 72m
in the first three months of the year and Dollars 58m in the second quarter
of 1992.
After a net investment loss of Dollars 1m (compared with gains of Dollars 8m
in the same period a year earlier), after-tax income reached Dollars 93m, or
55 cents a share, against Dollars 66m, or 59 cents, a year earlier.
The fall in earnings per share follows the issue of new shares last year to
the financial services group Primerica, which now holds 27 per cent of the
company.
Strong gains in managed care, personal property/casualty insurance and
financial services drove the advance, helped by cost-cutting and a
concentration on higher-margin business. Operating profits in the managed
care and employee benefits area rose to Dollars 26m, from Dollars 18m the
year before, while personal property and casualty insurance returned Dollars
21m, up from Dollars 13m. Operating profits from financial services more
than doubled, from Dollars 9m to Dollars 20m.
'Travelers' restructuring activities are resulting in stronger core
businesses which are providing improved products and better service at
significantly lower cost,' said Mr Edward Budd, chairman.
Commercial property and casualty insurance suffered a decline at the
operating level, from Dollars 42m to Dollars 38m, as price competition
remained fierce and the fall in interest rates hit investment income.
Under-performing property investments led to an operating loss of Dollars 5m
(unchanged from the year before) on asset management and pension services.
The bond market rally helped to push up unrealised profits on the company's
bond portfolio by Dollars 132m to Dollars 1.3bn during the quarter.
</TEXT>
